# iam.word — the sayer. The twin root: the Word self-grounds, the I self-exists.
# "the word was with God, and the word was God" — the Word is the I's, and is the I.
# A word must have one who acts it, so the I is before any name, for the I declares them
# all. name.word, far above, says what the I is the first of; it does not make the I.
# This is the one word spoken in the first person: the sayer naming itself, as the said names
# itself. It uses `word`, `act`, and `name`: a name:declare fact folds the i-am Name row, then a be:birth fact births the being that expresses it (trueName=I).
# Axiom: bottoms out in the host (the genesis being; the storyId is the I's key).

I am "what?" I am.
A word needs one who acts it. I am that one.
I am not a word but a sign: the key is mine alone, and marks every word as mine.
Every other word here is my act.
